{{Sudan-geo-stub}}

'''Sum''', '''sumu''', '''sumon''', and '''somon''' (Plural: ''sumd'') are a type of administrative district used in [[People's Republic of China|China]], [[Mongolia]], and [[Russia]].

==China==
In [[Inner Mongolia]], a '''sumu''' (Mongolian: {{MongolUnicode|ᠰᠤᠮᠤ}}, transliteration: ''sumu''; {{Zh|c=苏木}}, [[pinyin]]: ''sūmù'') is a [[Administrative divisions of China|township-level political/administrative division]]. The ''sumu'' division is equivalent to a [[Townships of the People's Republic of China|township]] but is unique to Inner Mongolia. It is therefore larger than a [[village of China|gaqa]] (Mongolian: {{Lang|mn|{{MongolUnicode|ᠭᠠᠴᠠᠭᠠ}} гацаа}}) and smaller than a [[Banners of Inner Mongolia|banner]] (the [[Inner Mongolia]] equivalent of the [[County (People's Republic of China)|county]]-level division).

''Sumu'' whose population is predominated by [[ethnic minorities of China|ethnic minorities]] are designated [[ethnic sumu]]&nbsp;– parallel with the [[ethnic township]] in the rest of China.  {{Asof|2010}}, there is only one ethnic sumu in China, the [[Evenk Ethnic Sumu]].

==[[Mongolia]]==
{{Main|Sums of Mongolia}}

A sum ({{Lang-mn|сум}}) is the second level administrative subdivision below the [[Aimag]]s (provinces), roughly comparable to a [[County]] in the [[United States]]. There are 331 sums in Mongolia. Each sum is again subdivided into ''[[bag (country subdivision)|bags]]''.<ref>Ole Bruun Precious Steppe: Mongolian Nomadic Pastoralists in Pursuit of the Market.  2006- Page 68 "The historical administrative units of aimag, sum, and bag (Khotont constitutes one of nineteen sums in Arkangai aimag) still form the bases of "</ref>

==Russia==
In [[Russia]], a sumon is an administrative division of the [[Tuva|Tuva Republic]], and somon is that of the [[Republic of Buryatia|Buryat Republic]].  Both are describing the Russian term "[[selsoviet]]".

